<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Stark QoL Pack: Time Scale Override

  Adjusts the game clock speed parameters to prevent simulation desync.
  The vanilla game advances the clock at a fixed rate regardless of whether
  the simulation has finished processing the current tick. When processing
  takes longer than the tick budget (common with 8+ Sims), the clock races
  ahead of the simulation, causing visible lag: Sims standing idle, head
  bobbing, Speed 3 running at Speed 1.

  This override reduces the clock advance rate at Speed 2 and Speed 3 to
  give the simulation more time to complete each tick before the clock
  advances. The result: fewer desync events, smoother simulation at high
  speed, and Sims that respond to player commands more quickly.

  Conflicts with:
    - MCCC "Game Time Speed" setting (both modify the same tuning)
    - SrslySims Simulation Lag Fix (functionally equivalent; do not stack)

  Compatible with:
    - TurboDriver's Simulation Unclogger (complementary)
-->
<I s="time_scale_override" n="StarkQoL_TimeScale">

  <!--
    Game clock multiplier at Speed 1 (normal).
    Vanilla: 25  |  StarkQoL: 25 (unchanged)

    No adjustment needed at normal speed; simulation easily keeps up.
    Unit: Sim-milliseconds per real-millisecond.
  -->
  <T n="speed_1_time_scale">25</T>

  <!--
    Game clock multiplier at Speed 2 (fast).
    Vanilla: 100  |  StarkQoL: 75

    25% reduction gives the simulation headroom on large lots.
    Perceptually, Speed 2 still feels fast but Sims don't freeze.
  -->
  <T n="speed_2_time_scale">75</T>

  <!--
    Game clock multiplier at Speed 3 (ultra speed).
    Vanilla: 1000  |  StarkQoL: 500

    50% reduction at Speed 3. This is where desync is most severe;
    the simulation simply cannot process 8+ Sims at 1000x clock rate.
    At 500x, Speed 3 still advances time quickly but maintains sync.
  -->
  <T n="speed_3_time_scale">500</T>

  <!--
    Low Performance Mode threshold (milliseconds of desync).
    Vanilla: 10000  |  StarkQoL: 5000

    The game enters Low Performance Mode when simulation falls this far
    behind the clock. Lowering the threshold triggers recovery earlier,
    preventing the long freeze-ups that occur when 10+ seconds of desync
    accumulate before the game reacts.
  -->
  <T n="low_performance_threshold_ms">5000</T>

</I>
